<subSubSection id="939B2B88CD610D1EB54B07F6AF9EB6B8" box="[314,446,1420,1447]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" type="description">
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD610D1EB54B07F6AF9EB6B8" blockId="15.[199,561,1387,1447]" box="[314,446,1420,1447]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">
(
<figureCitation id="43BA6486CD610D1EB53307F6AF96B6B8" box="[322,438,1420,1447]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[114,124,1453,1470]" captionTargetBox="[707,1179,215,1500]" captionTargetId="figure-435@14.[706,1179,825,1183]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 8. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia:A, Pecop- teris sp., transverse section of one vegetative pinnule showing thick lamina with palisade and aerenchyma mesophyll.Note the hair (arrow) attached near the lower extremity (SAR15B1T02); B, Scolecopteris cf. elegans Zenker, oblique transverse section of one pinnule showing two synangia attached on the left side. Note the thick lamina similar to that of Pecopteris sp. (A) but long thin pinnule extension on the right (SAR40C01); C, Scolecopteris cf. parvifolia Millay, part of a longitudinal section of one pinnule passing through several synangia. Note the relatively thin lamina, synangia borne on a short vascularised pedicel and solid tips of sporangia (SAR56AT02); D, E, Scolecopteris cf. alta Millay; D, longitudinal section of a synangium showing the characteristic central column; E, transverse sections of synangia, the one above is through the basal part of the synangium, the other is through the distal region showing only four dehiscent sporangia (SAR01C2B02). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596962/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Fig. 8D, E</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</heading>
<subSubSection id="939B2B88CD610D1EB40007B1AA09B032" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD610D1EB40007B1AA09B032" blockId="15.[113,646,1483,1573]" lastBlockId="15.[674,1211,216,1257]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">
This third 
<typeStatus id="043AC6A1CD610D1EB49207B1AF31B6F9" box="[227,273,1483,1510]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="1C810380CD610D1EB54407B1AF93B6FA" authorityName="Zenker" authorityYear="1837" box="[309,435,1483,1509]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Asterothecaceae" genus="Scolecopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Marattiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD610D1EB54407B1AF93B6FA" box="[309,435,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Scolecopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the less common but the most distinctive, with synangia circular in cross section, 
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD610D1EB5770470AF7CB53A" box="[262,348,1546,1573]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
in diameter and more than 
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD610D1EB6D402A2ACC2B3EC" box="[677,738,216,243]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
long, generally consisting of 6 sporangia fused in their basal half (along about 
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD610D1EB0710282AA79B20C" box="[1024,1113,248,275]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="600.0">600 µm</quantity>
) around a central column of parenchyma and fibers. Sporangia are less than 
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD610D1EB71A034DAD8BB24D" box="[875,939,311,338]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD610D1EB067034DAABDB24D" box="[1046,1181,311,338]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="300.0" valueMax="400.0" valueMin="200.0">200-400 µm</quantity>
in diameter with thin outer walls, even in their free distal region (
<figureCitation id="43BA6486CD610D1EB730030CADB9B28E" box="[833,921,374,401]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[114,124,1453,1470]" captionTargetBox="[707,1179,215,1500]" captionTargetId="figure-435@14.[706,1179,825,1183]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 8. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia:A, Pecop- teris sp., transverse section of one vegetative pinnule showing thick lamina with palisade and aerenchyma mesophyll.Note the hair (arrow) attached near the lower extremity (SAR15B1T02); B, Scolecopteris cf. elegans Zenker, oblique transverse section of one pinnule showing two synangia attached on the left side. Note the thick lamina similar to that of Pecopteris sp. (A) but long thin pinnule extension on the right (SAR40C01); C, Scolecopteris cf. parvifolia Millay, part of a longitudinal section of one pinnule passing through several synangia. Note the relatively thin lamina, synangia borne on a short vascularised pedicel and solid tips of sporangia (SAR56AT02); D, E, Scolecopteris cf. alta Millay; D, longitudinal section of a synangium showing the characteristic central column; E, transverse sections of synangia, the one above is through the basal part of the synangium, the other is through the distal region showing only four dehiscent sporangia (SAR01C2B02). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596962/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Fig. 8E</figureCitation>
). The synangium pedicels are very short, broad (
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD610D1EB7EB03ECADD5B2AE" box="[922,1013,406,433]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="600.0">600 µm</quantity>
), parenchymatous and attached to relatively thick (
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD610D1EB78803CCAA70B2CE" box="[1017,1104,438,465]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="400.0">400 µm</quantity>
) pinnules showing large mesophyll cells (
<figureCitation id="43BA6486CD610D1EB78303AFAA67B2EF" box="[1010,1095,469,496]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[114,124,1453,1470]" captionTargetBox="[707,1179,215,1500]" captionTargetId="figure-435@14.[706,1179,825,1183]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 8. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia:A, Pecop- teris sp., transverse section of one vegetative pinnule showing thick lamina with palisade and aerenchyma mesophyll.Note the hair (arrow) attached near the lower extremity (SAR15B1T02); B, Scolecopteris cf. elegans Zenker, oblique transverse section of one pinnule showing two synangia attached on the left side. Note the thick lamina similar to that of Pecopteris sp. (A) but long thin pinnule extension on the right (SAR40C01); C, Scolecopteris cf. parvifolia Millay, part of a longitudinal section of one pinnule passing through several synangia. Note the relatively thin lamina, synangia borne on a short vascularised pedicel and solid tips of sporangia (SAR56AT02); D, E, Scolecopteris cf. alta Millay; D, longitudinal section of a synangium showing the characteristic central column; E, transverse sections of synangia, the one above is through the basal part of the synangium, the other is through the distal region showing only four dehiscent sporangia (SAR01C2B02). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596962/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
) but there is no well-differentiated palisade tissue. These fertile pinnules clearly belong to the “Altus group” of 
<bibRefCitation id="BF1005F2CD610D1EB6D4004EAD1AB150" author="MILLAY M." box="[677,826,564,591]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref13316" refString="MILLAY M. 1979. - Studies of Paleozoic Marattialeans: a monograph of the American species of Scolecopteris. Palaeontographica B 169: 1 - 69." type="journal article" year="1979">Millay (1979)</bibRefCitation>
and they appear more similar to the Pennsylvanian 
<taxonomicName id="1C810380CD610D1EB739002EACC1B190" authority="(Watson) Millay, 1982" authorityName="Millay" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Watson" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Asterothecaceae" genus="Scolecopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Marattiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alta">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD610D1EB739002EADD8B171" box="[840,1016,596,622]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Scolecopteris alta</emphasis>
(Watson) Millay, 1982
</taxonomicName>
. The present material may also be compared to 
<taxonomicName id="1C810380CD610D1EB6B200E9AD98B1B2" box="[707,952,659,685]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Asterothecaceae" genus="Scolecopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Marattiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="globiforma">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD610D1EB6B200E9AD98B1B2" box="[707,952,659,685]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Scolecopteris globiforma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Grand-Croix and 
<taxonomicName id="1C810380CD610D1EB6D400C9ACD9B1D2" box="[677,761,691,717]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Asterothecaceae" genus="Scolecopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Marattiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="unita">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD610D1EB6D400C9ACD9B1D2" box="[677,761,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">S. unita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Lower Permian of Autun (
<bibRefCitation id="BF1005F2CD610D1EB0F900C9AD5EB1F1" author="MILLAY M. &amp; GALTIER J." pageId="15" pageNumber="58" pagination="163 - 171" refId="ref13372" refString="MILLAY M. &amp; GALTIER J. 1990. - Studies of Paleozoic Marattialean ferns: Scolecopteris globiforma n. sp. from the Stephanian of France. Review of Palaeobotany and Palynology 63: 163 - 171." type="journal article" year="1990">Millay &amp; Galtier 1990</bibRefCitation>
), however, these two species differ from the Sardinian pinnules by their thick outer sporangial walls bearing hairs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="939B2B88CD610D1EB6CA0148AA99B53A" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" type="description">
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD610D1EB6CA0148AA43B0D4" blockId="15.[674,1211,216,1257]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">These fertile fronds of marattialeans represent one of the most important elements of the flora but the taxonomic elucidation needs additional investigation, which is out of the scope of this paper – it will be the object of a separate, detailed study.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD610D1EB6CA01AAAD84B7F6" blockId="15.[674,1211,216,1257]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">
However, we wish to emphasize that the three distinct 
<typeStatus id="043AC6A1CD610D1EB770018AAD19B714" box="[769,825,1008,1035]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">types</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="1C810380CD610D1EB72F018AADFEB715" authorityName="Zenker" authorityYear="1837" box="[862,990,1008,1034]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Asterothecaceae" genus="Scolecopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Marattiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD610D1EB72F018AADFEB715" box="[862,990,1008,1034]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Scolecopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show differences in pinnule morphology and sporangial organization suggesting an important diversity of marattialeans at Perdasdefogu. In a palaeoecological perspective it is significant that most show rather thick pinnules (? xeromorph) which may have been efficient for water conservation in drier environments (see 
<bibRefCitation id="BF1005F2CD610D1EB6D406B4ADB8B7F6" author="BARTHEL M. &amp; WEISS H. - J." box="[677,920,1230,1257]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" pagination="45 - 56" refId="ref11647" refString="BARTHEL M. &amp; WEISS H. - J. 1997. - Xeromorphe Baumfarne im Rotliegend Sachsens. Veroffentlichungen des Museum fur Naturkunde Chemnitz 20: 45 - 56." type="journal article" year="1997">Barthel &amp; Weiss 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD610D1EB6D40774AD0FB63A" blockId="15.[677,1212,1294,1447]" box="[677,815,1294,1320]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">SEED PLANTS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD610D1EB6D40757ADC5B6B8" blockId="15.[677,1212,1294,1447]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">
Fragments of seed plants occur in less than 1 of 
<specimenCount id="CD87B38ACD610D1EB6D70736AD14B678" box="[678,820,1356,1383]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58" type="generic">4 specimens</specimenCount>
; they correspond to stems, leaves, rachises, seeds and pieces of cortex and wood of pteridosperms or cordaiteans.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD610D1EB6D407B1AA99B53A" blockId="15.[677,1209,1483,1573]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD610D1EB6D407B1AD40B6FA" box="[677,864,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Petiole or rachis of</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1C810380CD610D1EB71607B1ADD7B6F9" authorityName="Corda" authorityYear="1845" box="[871,1015,1483,1510]" class="Pteridospermopsida" family="Pteridospermopsida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Heterangium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pteridospermopsida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="15" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Heterangium</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD610D1EB78F07B6AAA6B6FA" box="[1022,1158,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">
<typeStatus id="043AC6A1CD610D1EB78F07B6AA06B6FA" box="[1022,1062,1484,1509]" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">type</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="43BA6486CD610D1EB04707B1AA5FB6FA" box="[1078,1151,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="58">Fig. 9J</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
Such isolated rachises with up to 6 mesarch bundles (arrows, 
