<subSubSection id="939B2B88CD7F0D00B6D4030CAD5AB0D4" pageId="17" pageNumber="60" type="description">
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD7F0D00B6D4030CAA09B28F" blockId="17.[677,1210,374,560]" box="[677,1065,374,401]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD7F0D00B6D4030CAA09B28F" box="[677,1065,374,401]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
Radially symmetrical ovules (
<figureCitation id="43BA6486CD7F0D00B7BE030DAA01B28F" box="[975,1057,374,401]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD7F0D00B6D403ECAA5FB12F" blockId="17.[677,1210,374,560]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
These rare, very small ovules (
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD7F0D00B79803ECAA55B2AE" box="[1001,1141,406,433]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.5">2.5 to 3 mm</quantity>
in diameter) show a well-marked radial symmetry with evidence of three sutures of the sclerotesta (arrows, 
<figureCitation id="43BA6486CD7F0D00B6D4038FACCFB10F" box="[677,751,501,528]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">Fig. 9J</figureCitation>
). Despite their small size, this is suggestive of affinities with medullosan pteridosperms.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD7F0D00B6D4002EAA0CB171" blockId="17.[675,1212,596,971]" box="[677,1068,596,622]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD7F0D00B6D4002EAA0CB171" box="[677,1068,596,622]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
Probable medullosan wood (
<figureCitation id="43BA6486CD7F0D00B7B6002EAA04B171" box="[967,1060,596,622]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="17.[113,123,1544,1561]" captionTargetBox="[144,622,215,1500]" captionTargetId="figure-322@17.[143,391,677,1137]" captionText="FIG. 10.— Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia:A-D, Da-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607887" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607887/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">Fig. 10E</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB3E7803CD7F0D00B6D4000EAD5AB0D4" blockId="17.[675,1212,596,971]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
A few fragments of wood, sometimes fusinized, show very broad tracheids (
<quantity id="1C79D5E6CD7F0D00B7CE00E9AA17B1B1" box="[959,1079,659,686]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="80.0" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="60.0">60-100 µm</quantity>
in diameter) with multiseriate (3 to 5-seriate) pitting on their radial walls and high multiseriate rays; they have characteristics of pteridosperm secondary xylem and may be attributed with some reservation to medullosans. This is supported by the occurrence of fragments of outer cortex, with parenchyma and sclerenchyma strands, of the 
<emphasis id="E9F5A411CD7F0D00B7BF0108AA1DB094" box="[974,1085,882,907]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">sparganum</emphasis>
- 
<typeStatus id="043AC6A1CD7F0D00B034010BAA54B093" box="[1093,1140,881,908]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">type</typeStatus>
which are characteristic of the stem and rachises of this group of seed ferns.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
